o write correctly, then leave\nadditional routing, multiple scopes per command, custom merge policy, and extra\nreporting for later.\n\n## Suggested Ref Shape\n\nAgentlog sync is key-scoped first. The serialized local ref and remote ref\nshould mirror that scope as directly as GitMeta allows:\n\n```text\nlocal:  refs/meta/local/agentlog\nremote: refs/meta/agentlog\n```\n\nThis is cleaner than publis\n[TRUNCATED]\n command.\n- Do not add `--push-only` or `--pull-only` until there is a concrete need.\n- If `--remote` is omitted, use `origin`.\n- The key scope/ref suffix should match the local GitMeta name for agentlog.\n- Keep the implementation as normal GitMeta exchange: serialize, fetch,\n  materialize, and push. Do not add custom backend ingestion or product-specific\n  sharing behavior for the POC.\n\n## Implementation Milestones\n\n1. Add `SyncScope` to `git-meta`.\n   - It should carry a name, local ref suffix/ref, remote ref suffix/ref, and a\n     key matcher.\n   - It should be general enough for non-GitButler callers.\n\n2. Add scoped sync bookkeeping in `git-meta`.\n   - Track serialization/materialization state per scope or per serialized ref.\n   - Keep the existing default/all-metadata lifecycle independent.\n\n3. Add scoped serialization in `git-meta`.\n   - Serialize only keys matched by the `SyncScope`.\n   - Write `refs/meta/local/<scope-name>` for the agentlog scope.\n   - Do not mutate persistent filter rules to achieve this.\n\n4. Add scoped materialization in `git-meta`.\n   - Materialize only keys matched by the `SyncScope`.\n   - Missing keys outside the scope must not affect local SQLite state.\n   - Missing remote ref means initial sync, not deletion.\n\n5. Add scoped push/fetch sync in `git-meta`.\n   - Fetch `refs/meta/<scope-name>` into its matching tracking ref when it\n     exists.\n   - Push `refs/meta/local/<scope-name>` to `refs/meta/<scope-name>`.\n   - Retry non-fast-forward with the boring fetch/materialize/serialize loop.\n\n6. A